{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01AATjLkFAvu43DwVBV3Sse4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now I have the state:\n- Namespace has `curl-test` and `openssl-toolbox` pods already running\n- TLS secret has `ca.crt`, `tls.crt`, `tls.key`\n- Password is `elasticpass`\n\nNow let me deploy a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster using native Kubernetes resources:\n1. A ConfigMap for Elasticsearch configuration\n2. A headless Service for inter-node communication\n3. A Service `es-http` for HTTPS access on port 9200\n4. A StatefulSet with 3 replicas\n5. A PodDisruptionBudget\nI need to configure Elasticsearch 8.x with security enabled, TLS for both the HTTP layer and inter-node transport, and set up discovery using the headless service. For the transport layer TLS, I can either reuse the same certificate if it's valid for the pod DNS names, or generate a separate one.\n\nActually, in ES 8.x with security enabled, transport TLS is mandatory, so I'll use the same certificate for both HTTP and transport layers. Now I'm setting up the elasticsearch.yml configuration with the cluster name, node discovery settings, and TLS paths for both the HTTP and transport layers.\n\nWriting configuration settings... I need to verify what the certificate actually covers before deciding whether to use it for transport TLS, since the node names need to be included as SANs or match a wildcard. I could disable hostname verification on the transport layer to avoid issues, but that's less secure, so let me first examine the certificate details to see what domains or names it's valid for.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":709,"cache_read_input_tokens":28631,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":709},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics